snippet.title: Mike Swap
snippet.description:
​Slowly but surely, Mike wound up replacing Mike in every single way. The car he drove, the girlfriend he smooched, the paychecks he collected, the parents he loved, the boxer shorts he stank up with his musty balls. Mike, on the other hand, didn't replace Mike in turn. No, that Mike just kinda wound up on the street, unable to hold a job or find suitable shelter from the elements. Then he got hit by a bus. Or something. We don't speak of Mike anymore. Only Mike exists.

Music Provided by our friends at Manhattan Murder Mystery
http://manhattanmurdermystery.bandcamp.com

snippet.title: 5sf's Comments of the Stream - 6/20
snippet.description:
Last Thursday we put on a live 4-hour show!! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HGDuvcJsR7E

And this week, in celebration of that monumental, totally-unrehearsed achievement and the fact that we're entering the homestretch of our Kickstarter, we thought we'd read comments solely from the Stream-A-Thon. In case you're wondering what that shrill, piercing shriek you're hearing every .4 seconds is, it's birds. In case you're wondering why, it's summer.

snippet.title: That Guy
snippet.description: ​We all have one friend like this. Mine's an 80's prog Jabba. Yours might be a Folk Boba. And Mary-Ellen's, well, doesn't take a Nawlins Jazz Salacious Crumb to see that she's rockin' a speed funk Lando Calrissian. I may have written the dumbest sentence in the history of mankind right now, and honestly I don't care.

snippet.title: Photobooth Confessional
snippet.description: Her mom just wants some invisible grandchildren before she gets whisked away to Unicorn Land. Is that so wrong? To want to hold up a ball of air and imagine it has your nose? Yet every time she brings it up, it's always with the "I need to work on my imaginary career" and the crying and the photographic proof that doesn't hold up in court. Yeesh, the kids these days. No commitment to fantasy.

snippet.title: Wishful Thinking
snippet.description: Just because people look like genies, doesn't give you the right to take a crap wherever you like. I made that mistake when I ran into George Clooney while he was vacationing at his Italian villa, sporting a mighty salt-and-pepper beard. I was promptly cast in "Syriana" as "Guy Who Shits Magnificently #3" but I couldn't bring the thunder on the day because I'm not a trained shitter or anything, so I was eventually cut from the film. But I respect George for seeing something in me that I didn't see myself.
